<NOTE PLACE="foot">(241.) Since the Proof of MIRACLES depends altogether on Report, or Tradition, which prevails mo&s;t in Times of Igno|rance, it &s;hould &s;eem to be a Mark of Weakne&s;s in Men of Learning, when they attempt to prove Truth, by tho&s;e Means, which fal&s;ify NATURE, and e&s;tabli&s;h Error. And in Reality no Evidence is &s;ufficient to prove a MIRACLE (in the common Ac|ceptation of that Word) unle&s;s it be &s;ufficient al&s;o to prove the Cour&s;e of NATURE, and the Experience of Sen&s;e to be in|con&s;i&s;tent. But we have proved before, that between NA|TURE and Experience there is a certain Corre&s;pondence, Pro|portion, or Harmony, on which all our Rea&s;oning depends. How then can MIRACLES prove TRUTH, when no Evidence le&s;s than that, which would de&s;troy all TRUTH, can prove a MIRACLE? Or how can we rea&s;on from that, which, if it could be proved to be true, would de&s;troy the very Foundation of Rea&s;on?</NOTE>
<L><PB N="35" REF="36">The fond Delu&s;ion of &s;uch cloudy Plea,</L>
